5/doc/releasenotes_ws650.html|title=VMware Workstation 6.5.0 Release Notes|work=VMware|date=October 15, 2008|accessdate=January 26, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Windows NT 4.0]]\n| 1.0\u20134.5\n|}\n</div>\n\n==Variants==\nThere was a free [[VMware Player]] distinct from Workstation, with similar but reduced functionality, until VMware Player v7, Workstation v11. In 2015 the two packages were combined as VMware Workstation 12, with a free '''VMware Workstation Player''' version which, on purchase of a license code, became the higher specification '''VMware Workstation Pro'''.<ref>[https://www.vmware.com/products/workstation VMware Web site, VMware Workstation Player Pro]</ref> VMware Workstation Player, like VMware Player<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vmware.com/download/eula/player40.html |title=VMware Player 4.0 EULA |publisher=VMware |accessdate=27 April 2012}}</ref> before it, is free of charge for non-commercial use, or for distribution or other use by written agreement.<ref name=download/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.vmware.com/workstation/2017/09/workstation-14-now-available.html |title=Workstation 14 Pro and Player Now Available!|website=VMware Workstation Zealot - Official blog of VMware Workstation|date=26 September 2017 |author=Michael Roy |accessdate= 19 October 2017}} VMware Workstation v14 (September 2017) continued to be free for non-commercial use.</ref> (Workstation ''Pro'' is also available for download for a free trial period, and is easily confused with the unlimited-time restricted-functionality version.)\n\n* VMware Workstation Player (formerly known as Player Pro),<ref>{{cite web\n | url         = https://www.vmware.com/products/player/features\n | title       = VMware Workstation Player (formerly known as Player Pro) \n | year        = 2015\n | website     = VMware\n | publisher   = VMware, Inc.\n | access-date = 2015-08-25\n | quote       = VMware Workstation 12 Player is a streamlined desktop virtualization application that runs one or more operating systems on the same computer without rebooting.}}</ref> free for non-commercial use; a license may be purchased for commercial use, also providing eligibility for paid support.<ref name=compare>{{cite web |url=https://www.vmware.com/uk/products/player/compare |title=VMware Player Pro: Compare to VMware Workstation 11 |newspaper=Vmware |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011200237/http://www.vmware.com/uk/products/player.html#compare |archivedate=11 October 2016 |url-status=live }} Version archived 11 October 2016 compares Workstation 12 Player to Player 7 Pro; Workstation 12 Player (Unlicensed) to Workstation 12 Player (Licensed); and Workstation 12 Player to Workstation 12 Pro. Page is updated; as of October 2017 compares Workstation Player and Workstation Pro, only</ref>\n\n* VMware Workstation Pro,<ref>{{cite web\n| url         = https://www.vmware.com/products/workstation/features.html\n| title       = VMware Workstation Pro \n| year        = 2015\n| website     = VMware\n| publisher   = VMware, Inc.\n| access-date = 2015-08-25\n| quote       = }}</ref> available for a 30-day free trial before purchase but distinct from the permanently free version.\n\nThe features of the versions are compared on the VMware web site.<ref name=compare/>\n\n==VMware Tools==\nVMware Tools, a package with drivers and other software available for the various guest operating systems VMware products support, installs in guest operating systems to add functionality. Tools is updated from time to time, with v10.1.15 in September 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://docs.vmware.com/en/VMware-Tools/10.1.15/rn/vmware-tools-10115-release-notes.html |title=VMware Tools 10.1.15 Release Notes |website=VMware|date=26 September 2017 |author= |accessdate=19 October 2017}}</ref> It has several components, including the following:\n\n* Drivers for emulated hardware:\n** VESA-compliant graphics for the guest machine to access high screen resolutions\n** Network drivers for the vmxnet2 and vmxnet3 [[Network card|NIC]]\n** [[Ensoniq AudioPCI]] audio\n** Mouse integration\n* Support of shared folders and drag-and-drop file transfer between host and guest. This functionality is described as HGFS (Host Guest File System), and may be disabled by default for security; it may be enabled by changes to the .VMX configuration file\n* Clipboard sharing between host and guest\n* Time-synchronization capabilities (guest synchronizes with host machine's clock)\n* Support for Unity, a feature that allows seamless integration of applications with the host desktop<ref>{{cite web\n | url         = https://pubs.vmware.com/workstation-9/index.jsp?topic=%2Fcom.vmware.ws.using.doc%2FGUID-8C477788-7700-4030-8C4A-039C02AABB74.html\n | title       = Use Unity Mode\n | website     = VMware Workstation 9 Documentation Center\n | publisher   = VMware\n | access-date = 2015-08-25\n | quote       = In Unity mode, virtual machine applications appear on the host system desktop}}</ref> by hiding virtual monitor and drawing the windows of applications running in the virtual machine on the host. Unity support was added for Windows 10 and removed for Linux in Workstation 12.<ref name=disunity>{{cite web |url=http://planetvm.net/blog/?p=2936 |title=VMware Workstation 12 discards unity support for Linux \u00bb PlanetVM |newspaper=Planetvm.net |date=  |author=Wil van Antwerpen|accessdate= 11 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Third-party resources==\n\n===Ready-to-use virtual machines===\nMany ready-made virtual machines (VMs) which run on VMware Player, Workstation, and other virtualization software are available<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vmware.com/appliances/directory/ |title=VMware Virtual Machine Marketplace, with 3691 entries (not all still available) as of 2 June 2016 |publisher=Vmware.com |date= |accessdate=2 June 2016}}</ref> for specific purposes, either for purchase or free of charge; for example free [[Linux]]-based \"browser appliances\" with the [[Firefox]] or other browser installed<ref>{{cite web|url=https://solutionexchange.vmware.com/store/products/browser-appliance |title=Browser Appliance |publisher=Vmware.com |date= |accessdate=2014-04-05}}</ref><ref name=ba>[http://browser.shell.tor.hu/ Browser Appliance]. Includes brief documentation, including \"autoRevert on shutdown\"</ref> which can be used for safe Web browsing; if infected or damaged it can be discarded and replaced by a clean copy. The appliance can be configured to automatically reset itself after each use so personal information and other changes are not stored.<ref name=ba/> VMs distributed legally only have freely distributable [[operating system]]s, as operating systems on VMs must be licensed; ready-to-use Microsoft Windows VMs, in particular, are not distributed, except for evaluation versions.\n\n===Other tools===\n* PowerWF<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.powerwf.com/ |title=powerwf.com |publisher=powerwf.com |accessdate=2012-09-13 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120815180250/http://powerwf.com/ |archive-date=2012-08-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref> - Provides a visual representation of VMware VIX scripts, converting them into workflows, or converting workflows into Powershell cmdlets and modules. VIX is VMware's addition to Microsoft's Powershell for automation of the VMware Player.\n\n==See also==\n* [[OS level virtualization]]\n* [[x86 virtualization]]\n*[[VirtualBox|Virtualbox]]\n*[[Comparison of platform virtualization software]]\n*\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|VMware}}\n* [https://www.vmware.com/products/workstation/ VMware Workstation product page]\n* [http://www.vmware.com/content/dam/digitalmarketing/vmware/en/pdf/support/product-lifecycle-matrix.pdf VMware Lifecycle Product Matrix]\n{{Virtualization software}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vmware Workstation}}\n[[Category:VMware|Workstation]]\n[[Category:Virtualization software]]\n[[Category:Windows software]]\n[[Category:Proprietary cross-platform software]]\n[[Category:1998 software]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox software\n| name                 = VMware Workstation\n| logo                 = VMware Workstation 11.0 icon.png\n| logo caption         = VMware Workstation v11.0 icon\n| screenshot           = WMware Workstation 11.1 screenshot.png\n| caption              = Screenshot showing VMware Workstation 11.1 on [[Windows 7]]\n| collapsible          = \n| author               = \n| developer            = [[VMware]]\n| released             = 1999<ref name=\"ThiruvathukalHinsen2010\">{{cite journal\n | last1   = Thiruvathukal\n | first1  = George K\n | last2   = Hinsen\n | first2  = Konrad\n | last3   = L\u00e4ufer\n | first3  = Konstantin\n | last4   = Kaylor\n | first4  = Joe\n | date    = 2010\n | title   = Virtualization for Computational Scientists\n | journal = Computing in Science & Engineering\n | volume  = 12\n | issue   = 4\n | pages   = 52\u201361\n | issn    = 1521-9615\n | doi     = 10.1109/MCSE.2010.92\n | url     = https://ecommons.luc.edu/cs_facpubs/16}}</ref>\n| latest release version = 15.5.2 Pro<ref>{{cite web\n | url        = https://docs.vmware.com/en/VMware-Workstation-Pro/15.5/rn/VMware-Workstation-1552-Pro-Release-Notes.html\n | title      = VMware Workstation 15.5.2 Pro Release Notes\n | date       = March 12, 2020\n | accessdate = March 15, 2020}}</ref><br>\n| latest release date  = {{Start date and age|2020|03|12|df=yes}}\n| status               = Active\n| programming language = [[C (programming language)|C]], [[C++]]\n| operating system     = [[Windows]]<br />[[Linux]]\n| platform             = [[x86-64]] only<ref name=sysreq-hostOS>{{cite web\n | title      = Processor Requirements for Host Systems\n | url        = https://pubs.vmware.com/workstation-9/index.jsp?topic=%2Fcom.vmware.ws.get_started.doc%2FGUID-BBD199AA-C346-4334-9F56-5A42F7328594.html\n | work       = VMware Workstation 9 Documentation Center\n | publisher  = VMware\n | accessdate = 12 December 2012}}</ref><br />(version 11.x and above, previous versions were available for [[x86]] as well)\n| language             = <!--Anything besides English? With a source please. -->\n| genre                = [[Hypervisor]]\n| license              = [[Freeware]] (Workstation Player) [[Trialware]] and commercial (Workstation Pro)\n| website              = {{Official URL}}\n| frequently updated   = \n}}\n\n'''VMware Workstation Pro''' is a hosted [[hypervisor]] that runs on [[x64]] versions of Windows and Linux operating systems<ref>https://kb.vmware.com/selfservice/microsites/search.do?language=en_US&cmd=displayKC&externalId=2129859</ref> (an [[x86]] version of earlier releases was available);<ref name=sysreq-hostOS /> it enables users to set up [[virtual machine]]s (VMs) on a single physical machine, and use them simultaneously along with the actual machine. Each virtual machine can execute its own [[operating system]], including versions of [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Linux]], [[BSD]], and [[MS-DOS]]. VMware Workstation is developed and sold by [[VMware, Inc.]], a division of [[Dell Technologies]]. There is a free-of-charge version, VMware Workstation Player, for non-commercial use. An operating systems license is needed to use proprietary ones such as Windows. Ready-made Linux VMs set up for different purposes are available from several sources.\n\nVMware Workstation supports [[bridging (networking)|bridging]] existing host [[network adapter]]s and sharing physical [[disk drive]]s and [[Universal Serial Bus|USB]] devices with a virtual machine. It can simulate disk drives; an [[ISO image]] file can be [[mount (computing)|mounted]] as a virtual [[optical disc drive]], and virtual [[hard disk drive]]s are implemented as [[.vmdk]] files.\n\nVMware Workstation Pro can save the state of a virtual machine (a \"snapshot\") at any instant. These snapshots can later be restored, effectively returning the virtual machine to the saved state,<ref>{{cite web |last=Warren |first=Steven |url=http://blogs.techrepublic.com.com/virtualization-coach/?p=143 |title=Snapshots in VMware Workstation |publisher=Blogs.techrepublic.com.com |date=2008-11-20 |accessdate=2012-09-13 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120707022902/http://blogs.techrepublic.com.com/virtualization-coach/?p=143 |archive-date=2012-07-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref> as it was and free from any post-snapshot damage to the VM.\n\nVMware Workstation includes the ability to group multiple virtual machines in an inventory folder. The machines in such a folder can then be powered on and powered off as a single object, useful for testing complex client-server environments.\n\n==2016 company changes and future development==\nVMware Workstation versions 12.0.0, 12.0.1, and 12.1.0 were released at intervals of about two months in 2015.<ref name=download>{{cite web |url=https://my.vmware.com/web/vmware/free#desktop_end_user_computing/vmware_workstation_player/12_0 |title=Download VMware Workstation Player|website=VMware |date= |author=<!--not stated--> |accessdate= 11 May 2016}} Download site for VMware Player 7.x and Workstation Player 12.x</ref> In January 2016 the entire development team behind VMware Workstation and Fusion was disbanded and all US developers were immediately fired.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ir.vmware.com/default.aspx?SectionId=5cc5ecae-6c48-4521-a1ad-480e593e4835&LanguageId=1&PressReleaseId=e2fb62b8-b4a0-4a64-853b-bce3b3b51948 |title=VMware Reports Fourth Quarter and Full Year 2015 Results |website=ir.vmware.com |date=26 January 2016 |author=<!--not stated--> |accessdate= 13 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = VMware axes Fusion and Workstation US devs|url = https://www.theregister.co.uk/2016/01/27/vmware_fusion_and_workstation_development_team_fired/|access-date = 2016-01-28|last = Cloud|last2 = Security|last3 = Australia|last4 = Vmware|last5 = Microsoft|first6 = VMware axes Fusion and Workstation US|last6 = devs|first7 = new multi-cloud plan will ensure growth|last7 = VMware says vSphere in decline|first8 = vows to focus on 'core products'|last8 = Citrix kills Sydney research lab}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = VMware Confirms Layoffs In Earnings Statement As It Prepares For Dell Acquisition|url = https://techcrunch.com/2016/01/26/vmware-confirms-layoffs-in-earnings-statement-as-it-prepares-for-dell-acquisition/|website = TechCrunch|access-date = 2016-01-28|first = Ron|last = Miller}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = A Tribute to VMware Workstation, Fusion, and Hosted UI|url = http://blog.chipx86.com/2016/01/26/a-tribute-to-vmware-workstation-fusion-and-hosted-ui/|website = ChipLog|access-date = 2016-01-28|last = chipx86}}</ref> The company said that \"the restructuring activities will not impact the existence of any current product lines\", that \"roles and responsibilities associated with particular businesses will be moved to other regions and office locations\", and that investment would continue \"with emphasis on our growth products\". The future of Workstation and Fusion became uncertain. On 24 April 2016 maintenance release 12.1.1 was released. In September, same year, the company announced that \"we\u2019re very much alive and well\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2016/08/vmware-says-were-not-dead-updates-fusion-and-workstation-for-free/|title=VMware says, \"We're not dead,\" updates Fusion and Workstation for free|date= 30 August 2016 | author=Jon Brodkin | website=ARS Technica}}</ref> Consequently, on September 13 Workstation 12.5 and Fusion 8.5 were released as free upgrades which added support for [[Windows 10#Redstone|Windows 10 Anniversary edition]] and [[Windows Server 2016]].\n\n==Version history==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Legend\n|-\n! Color\n! Meaning\n|-\n| style=\"background:salmon;\" | Red\n| Unsupported release\n|-\n| style=\"background:#a0e75a;\" | Green\n| Current or still supported release\n|-\n| style=\"background:skyBlue;\" | Blue\n| Future release\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Version\n! Rele